All right, I can't look too closely at it right now... maybe later; but the regex spooked me.



s/\s*(.*?)\s*/$1/;



I doubt that will does what you want.  You might want to split that into two:



s/^\s+//;s/\s+$//;



Take a look at the following:

-------------------------------

my @strings;



push @strings, 'nospace';

push @strings, 'trailingspace      ';

push @strings, '      leadingspace';

push @strings, 'internal space';



for(@strings)

{

	print "Before: '$_'\n";

	s/\s*(.*?)\s*/$1/;

	print "After: '$_'\n\n\n";

}



Outputs:

Before: 'nospace'

After: 'nospace'





Before: 'trailingspace      '

After: 'trailingspace      '





Before: '      leadingspace'

After: 'leadingspace'





Before: 'internal space'

After: 'internal space'

>  Wouldn't s/^\s*(\S.*?)\s*$/$1/; work



Yes, it would; but it is doing too much.  On the first part, why match on 0 spaces?  On the end, why match on 0 spaces?  At the very least, change those to + signs a la: s/^\s+(\S.*?)\s+$/$1/;.  Even then, why match 1 or more spaces, then match on a non-space?  Of course that is going to happen or the regex will fail in the case of all spaces.  Basically, the idiomatic perl way to strip leading and trailing spaces is for(@array) { s/^\s+//, s/\s+$// }



P.S.  It's hard to make comments legible without 'br' and 'p' tags, at least.

Hi there,



I searched a long time how to get my RDF-/RSS-Files correctly styled in IE.



They are correctly displayed in Opera and Mozilla, but IE just doesn't accept

any rules for tags that have an "rdf:" or "dc:" or any other namespace before them.



If you write:

RDF

{

  /* ... */

}

the &lt;rdf:RDF&gt;-Element is correctly styled in Mozilla and Opera but not in IE.



But if you write:

rdf\:RDF

{

  /* ... */

}

the &lt;rdf:RDF&gt;-Element is correctly styled in IE! Opera also understands that

workaround, but Mozilla doesn't. So you just write:

rdf\:RDF, RDF

{

  /* ... */

}

and everybody is happy. :-)



There should be no need for any "|"-Selector or any @namespace.



Hope that helps,

Alexander Koch



PS: Please excuse my bad English ;-)
